'42 102%\nPan-Amer Pete 6s '4O 75\nParamount Broadway 5%s 'sl 1.09%\nParamount Lasky Famous 6s \u2019ll'.. 92%\nPathe Exchange 7s '37 60%\nPenn Dixie Cement 6s \u20194l 71\nPennsylvania 4%s \u201965 100\nPennsylvania 4%s '6O 96%\nPennsylvania 5s '64 101 Vi\nPhiladelphia Co 5s \u201967 98\nPhila Reading C I 6s M 9... 71%\nPitts Cin Chi ft St I. 4Rs 99%\nPostal Tel Cable 5s \u201953 55 Vi\nPub Ser Gas Elec 4R\u00bb 101%\nReading 4Rs A \u201997 99%\nSt L San Francisco 5s 8.... 97%\nSt L San Francisco 4%s 76%\nSt L I M Gulf 4s 98\nSt Louis Southwest 4s 99%\nSeaboard Air L Fla 6s A 10\nShell Pipe Line 5s 83%\nShell Uninn Gil 5\u00ab 86\nSinclair Oil 7s A 94\nSkelly Oil 5%s 78\nSouthern Pacific 4s 93%\nSouthern Pacific 4s 00l 90\nSouthern Ry 6s 109\nSouthern Rv 6%s 114\nStandard Oil N J 5s 103\nS W Bell Tel 5s 104%\nTexas Corp 5s 99%\nTranscontinental Oil 6%5........ 109%\nUnion Pacific 4s 97%\nUnion Pacific 4%s 98%\nU S Rubber 5s 69%\nVirginia Ry 5s 99\nWabash Ry 5s B 92\nWestern Electric 5s 105\nWestern Maryland 5%s 92%\ny.estern Union 5s 51....... 102%\nBrokerage Margin\nRequirements Cut\nShields Co., stock exchange\nmembers, are permitting clients to\ncarry on margin stocks selling for\n$7 a share or more because of the\nlarge number of stobks which have\ndeclined below $lO a share, the\nformer minimum price require\nment. On stocks which will be\ncarried on margin a minimum\nmargin of $4 a share will be re\nquired.\nBowie Chipman, Broker,\nIs Fine Sailor\n\u2014\u2014het\nGEORGE BOWIE CHIFMAN\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nWestern Union 5\" 1...... 1*2%\nWestern Union 6%e 168\nWheeling Steel 4%e 89%\nYngetown H ft T 5a 191%\nForeign Bonds\nArgentine 6s A V..... M 91\nAustria 7\u00bb 105%\nAustralia 5s 57.,.. 73\nAustralia 5s 55 74%\nBelgium 6%s 107\nBelgium 7s \u201956 107%\nBelgium 7s 55... 111%\nBelgium 8s 197\nBolivia 8s ........aaaal 47%\nBrasil 6a 27..... |7\nBrazil 6%s 26 57\nBrazil 8s 41 72\nCsldas 7%a J\nCanada 4%s 104\nCanada Bs 31\nChlle 6s 60\nChile 6 S 61 76\nChile 6s 61 Jan... 74\nCuba ts \u2019#4-\u201944.... 98\nCuba 5%s 48\nCzechoslovakia 8s\nDenmark 6s 104%\nDominican Rep S%s 87\nFranco-Amcr 7%s \u201943... mist\nFrench 7%, \u201941..... I\u201d\nFrench 7s \u201949 129\nGerman Bank 7s 'SO 80%\nGerman Gen Elec 6s 86\nGerman Rep 7s \u201949 101%\nHaiti 6s \u201952 <*6\nHungarian L M 7%s A 80\nItaly 7s \u2019sl 92%\nJapanese 5%s 91%\nJapanese 6%s \u2019S4 102%\nMilan 6%s \u201952.. 74%\nNord Ry 6%s '54 105\nOriental Development <e 'Bl *4\nOslo 6%s \u201846 161\nParis Lyons Med 6s \u2019SB 104%\nPeru 6s \u20196l sg\nPeru 7 s's 9 jju\nPoland 6s \u201944 88%\nQueensland 7s \u20194l 94\nRio de Janeiro B%e \u201952 60%\nRome 6%s \u201952 78\nSaxon Publie Works 6%s \u2019Bl 73\nSaxon Public Works 7s \u201946 77\nSeine Department 7\u00bb \u201942 107\nSerbia 7* \u201962....... 78,\nSwiss Confederation 5%a \u201944 105%\nTokyo B%a \u2019ll 18%\nUruguay 6s \u201964 74%\nYokohama 6s \u20196l 95%\nACGIDENTGAIN\nIS SHOWN\nBy FRANK F. LOOMIS\nIn payment of accident claims\nalready reported, more than $92,-\n000,000 has been distributed to\npolicyholders and their bene\nficiaries' in every part of the\nUnitew States and Canada as a\nresult of injuries and deaths suf\nfered in every conceivable kind\nof an accident.\nRecent statistics indicate that\n31 persons out of every 100 in\njured in accidents are hurt in\nmotor vehicle mishaps. Deaths, as\na result of an automobile acci\ndent, in the United States this\nyear will be approximately 32,000\nwhich is an increase of 4 per\ncent over the fatality toll of last\nyear, it is indicated by reports.\nThe gain in the number of per\nsons killed will make this year's\nfatality toll 155 per cent greater\nthan it was in 1920 and 46 per\ncent greater than the 1925 figure\nof automobile accident deaths.\nHome Accidents\nAccidents in the home are re\nsponsible for the second largest\npercentage of accidents, with 26\n{>ersons out of 100 accident vic\nims. Sports and recreation claim\nthird place, with approximately\n20 persons out of every 100 being\ninjured in such activities. Pedes\ntrians then follow in the fre\nquency of those injured, the ratio\nbeing 13 out of every 100, exclu\nsive of motor vehicle mishaps.\nThe every-day doings of people,\nsuch as traveling in an automo\nbile, staying at home, attending\nto business and shopping as pedes\ntrians. and taking part in sports\nand other forms of recreational\nactivity, are responsible for the\ndisabilities suffered by 81 victims\nout of every 100 persons injured.\nChances SHght\nWith one person out of every\n10 of the entire population in\njured in accidents each year, the\nfigures indicate that the chances\nof avoiding injury in one or more\nof the common causes of accident 9\nis rather slight during an adult\u2019s\nli\u20193 time. While you may not be\nable to avoid being a victim of\nsome accident, of a commonplace\nor even freakish nature, you can\nprepare yourself against a finan\ncial loss as a result of such acci\ndent. There are 73,200,000 busi\nness days are lost each year be\ncause of auto accidents alone. Do\nnot wait until the accident occurs\nbefore realizing the importance\nof this form of insurance cover\nage, which is absolutely essential\nfor men and women dependent on\ntheir' ability to work and earn\nmoney for their living.\nGeorge Bowie Chipman, resi\ndent partner of Harriman Co.\nhere, has an enviable reputation\nas a yachtman along the whole\nAtlantic coast.\nLast summer the Washington\nbroker sailed his boat to his\nsummer home at Castine, Me., and\nreturn. He has made many trips\nalong the seaboard, some of them\nof a greatly extended nature.\nMr. Chipman, in addition to\nhis duties as a partner in the\nstock exchange firm, is a director\nin a number of commercial firms.\nHe is a thirty-second degree\nMason and a member of several\nlocal clubs. He has one son.\nNorris.\nBritish Steel Trade\nFalls in November\nBritish imports, exports and\nproduction of Iron and steel all\ndeclined in November, according\nto a cablegram received from\nRonald Renshaw, acting com\nmercial attache. \u25a0by the Depart\nment of Commerce.\n2 POWER TROST\nFOES DUE\nFORAX\nNew Commissioners Interpret\nLaw as Vacating All Posts;\nImperils Russell and King\nThe new Federal Power Com\nmission, taking control over the\nnation\u2019s water powers, at once put\nItself in position to drop at will the\ntwo officials leading the fight to\nsqueeze approximately $500,000,000\nof \u201cwater\u201d out of power company\ncapital.\nChairman George Otis Smith\nannounced after he was sworn,\nthat the amended water power\nlaw has been interpreted as va\ncating all positions on the old\ncommission\u2019s staff, which must\nbe filled by appointment or re\nappointment.\nSilent on Two Men\nHe refused to predict the fate\nof Solicitor Charles A. Russell and\nChief Accountant William V.\nKing, who have blocked approval\nof \u201cwatered\u201d accounts but failed\nto obtain their rejection.\nSmith contented himself with:\n\u201cI have made no pledges.\u201d\nA move to oust Russell has\nbeen in the making for several\nI weeks, following his clash with\nthe Administration over the pro\nposed surrender of regulation in\nthe New River test case and his\ncharges that the Pennsylvania\nutilities commission permitted the\npublic to be \u201cslim-slammed\" out\nof $6,000,000.\nKing Long Fought\nAlthough no open move has\nbeen made against King, the\npower Interests have fought for\n10 years against his searching\nexaminations of their accounts.\nVacating of the offices was\nunderstood to be based on an\ninformal opinion from Attorney\nGeneral Mitchell. Smith declined\nto confirm or deny this, but said\nthe new commissioners had \u201ccon\nsulted some of the law officers.*\u2019\nThe new law reads that the com\nmission \u201cshall be deemed to be\nreorganized\u201d when three com\nmissioners have taken office.\nMILUDN AIDED\nBTFAHMAGT\nr J\nMore than 1,000 farmers have\nbeen aided by the agricultural\nmarketing act, the Federal Farm\nBoard announced today in a bul\nletin describing how farmers, with\nGovernment assistance, can set up\nco-operative machinery, owned and\ncontrolled by themselves, to mar\nket their crops.\nSeven national agencies have\nbeen established by co-operatives\nwith the assistance of the board.\nSix of these are sales agencies.\nFive already are operating, mar\nketing grain, cotton, livestock,\nwool and mohair, and pecans.\nThere are 12,000 farmer-owned\nand controlled co-operative asso\nciations in the United States, the\nmembership totaling 3.100,000,\nrepresenting about 2,000,000 farm\ners.\nThe bulletin said approximately\n2,000,000 bales of 1930 short-staple\ncotton had been delivered to the\nAmerican Cotton Co-operative As\nsociation up to December 1. More\nthan 500,000 additional bales prob\nably will be delivered during the\nwinter and spring months.\nMore than 150,000 growers are\nmembers of the 11 State and re\ngional associations which form\nthe association.\nHartford Brokers\nIn Receivership\nHARTFORD, Dec. 22.\u2014Judge\nE. E. Dickinson, in the Superior\nCourt of this State, placed T. E.\nKingston Co., security dealers,\nin temporary receivership as a\nresult of action instituted by As\nsistant Attorney General J. H.\nKing, acting for L. E. Shippee,\nbank commissioner.\nThree offices of the Connecti\ncut Trading Corp., a subsidiary\nof the brokerage house, were ar\nrested today on bench warrants\ncharging perjury. Those arrested\nwere John H. Reid, president\nand treasurer of the concern;\nFrank H. Smith, vice president\nand assistant treasurer, and Ed\nmund J. Grandhal, secretary.\nThey are accused of swearing\nfalsely, in an application to the\nsecretary of State, that the $55,-\n000 original capital of the com\npany had been paid in cash.\nOIL STOCKS\n(Furnlzhed by W. B. Hlbbz ft Co.)\nI Bld. I Ask,\nBorne Scrymser 10 13\nBuckeye Pipe Line 42 44\nChezebore Mfr C 0.......... 104 115\nContinental Oil 6 10\nCumberland Pipe Line...... 20 25\nEureka Pipe Line 25 33\nGalena Siffnal Oil c0m..... 2 3\nHumble Oil 61 63\nRia. Pipe Line 315 320\nImperial Oil Canada 15% 16\nIndiana Pipe Line 17 18\nInternational Pete 12% 13\nNational Tranait 1 12 13%\nN Y Transportation 12 14\nNorthern Pipe Linea 26 31\nPenna Mex Fuel 13 15\nSolar Ref Co 78%\nSouthern Pipe Line.... 10\nSouth Penn OH 19 20%\nSoutheastern Pipe Line..., 32 36\nStandard Oil of Indiana.... 34 34%\nStandard Oil of Keutubky. 19% 20\nStandard Oil of Nebraska.. 84 36\nStandard OH of Ohio 44 44\nStandard OH of Ohio pfd.\u00bb. 115 116\nSwen and Fink 4 10\nVacuum OH ........i....., 54% 55%\nTA\u00ab National Daily\nBAIL PLANS SEEN\nAS PROSPERITY\nRETURNAID\nHeads of Railroads Predict\nProposed Merger of Four\nLines Will Boom Industry\nBy W. S. COUSINS\nNEW YORK, Dec. 23 (1.N.5.).\nConsolidation of important East\nern American railroads into four\nmajor trunk lines will, in all\nprobability, constitute one of the\nprominent factors in the return\nof prosperity to the transporta\ntion industry.\nThis, in brief, is the hope held\nout by the leaders of the rail\nIndustry, some of whom are now\nmeeting in New York in an effort\nto find a solution for the con\nsolidation problem.\nWants Even Break\nJ. J. Bernet, president of the\nChesapeake and Ohio Railway\nCompany, said:\n\u201cThe railroads only want an\neven break. They think that\nthe Federal Government or the\nState governments ought not to\nbe competing with them by\nsupplying service below cost\nand charging the deficit to the\ntaxpayers.\n\u201cMore than 20 per cent of\nall the employment in the\nUnited States is furnished by\nthe railroads, directly or in\ndirectly. This fact is the key\nto why, during 1930, the coun\ntry had a demonstration of the\noften-repeated warning that it\ncould not be prosperous if the\nrailroads were depressed.\u201d\nPickup Is Seen\nSaid J. J. Pelley, president of\nthe New York. New Haven and\nHartford railroad:\n\u201cWe are going to have an\nimprovement next year. While\nthe early part of the year will\nprobably continue at low levels,\nwe expect a definite upward\nturn sometime during the year,\nwith gradual and progressive\nrecovery from then on.\u201d\nEdward E. Loomis, president* of\nthe Lehigh Valley Railroad Com\npany, said that the recent action\non the part of the railroads them\nselves as to future policy, which\nwas followed by some most con\nstructive recommendations by the\nInterstate Commerce Commission,\nin its report to Congress, promise\nto put the problems of the in\ndustry clearly before the public\nand a better understanding of\nthem must surely follow.\nCONSTRUCTION\nNEED CITED\nNEW YORK, Dec. 23 <I.NJS.).\nMore than $4,500,000,000 worth\nof major public improvements are\nneeded in the United States at\nthe present time, according to a\nreport completed here yesterday\nby S. W. Strauss Co., after a\nsurvey of 236 chambers of com\nmerce in leading cities through\nout the country. In this estimate\nno allowance was made for pri\nvate work, such as residential\nbuildings, office structures, apart\nments, theaters and factories.\nOs the work that is needed,\nonly $1,200,000,000 of the con\nstruction by Federal, State, county\nand municipal governments, is\nnow under way. The remaining\namount has been held up, de\nlayed, or postponed for various\nreasons, the report stated.\nNew York city alone needs sl,-\n300,000,000 of public construction,\naccording to the report, of which\n$660,000,000 1$ going forward at\nthe present time. Chicago\u2019s needs\nare set at $500,000,000 exclusive of\nworld fair buildings, with $37,-\n000,000 under way. The projected\nTemple of Music and Art and a\nrailroad terminal provide two\nthirds of Philadelphia\u2019s estimate\nof $330,000,000 needed.\nWall Street\nHears\nThat many old English and\nScotch investment trusts bought\ndividend paying American\nshares during the last recession.\nThat Standard Oil of New\nYork (NY) is an attractive in\nvestment purchase at its pres\nent level, where it gives a\nhigher yield than it has at any\ntime in the last 18 years.\nThat National Power and\nLight INPL) will net about\n$2.24 a share this year, against\n$2.17 a share last year, and\nthat Electric Bond and Share\n(EBS) on the Curb has in\ncreased its holdings to 44 per\ncent.\nThat considerable scale buy\ning is coming into Columbian\nCarbon (CNB).\nThat Westinghouse Airbrake\n(WKM) will cover its $2 divi\ndend by a comfortable margin\nthis year.\nThat Evans Auto Loading Co.\nwill show a net lorn of about\n$259,999 this year, compared\nwith a net profit of $802,399\nlast year.\nTUESDAY\u2014DECEMBER 23\u20141930\nN. Y. Curb Market\n(Furnlzhud by W, B. Hlbbu a Co\nHighl Low L\u2014t\nAlum Co of Am I*s 14* 14*\nAm Comnw a o\u00abo I 11% 11% 11%\nAm Dept 1% 1% 1%\nAm Eyultiez,... 4% 4% 4%\nAm F Pw 14% 14% 14%\nAm Foundere 3% 3% 3%\nAm Gao ft El 78% 78 78%\nAm Gas ft El pfd 164% 104% 104%\nAm Inv Inc B 4% 4% 4%\ntAm Licht ft T...... 40% 40% 40%\nAm Mfg... 34 34 34\nAm Maracaibo %J\nAm Natl Gaa...\u2019. *%f 8% 3%\nAm Superpwr 9% 9% 9%:\nAm Buperpwr 1 pfd.. 81 81 13\nI Am Util ftO Cp 8.... 1% 3% 3%\nAnclo Ch 11 Nit 10 8% 8%\nAppalac Gaa 6% 5% 5%\nArk Natl Gaa A...... 5% 5% 5%\nAmo Elec Ind 4% 4% 4%\nAaao Gaa A....k 15 14% 15\nAssoc Gas db rt 1% 1% 1%\nAsso Rayon\nAsao Rayon pf 81% 11% 31%\nAH Fruit ft 5ue.,...1 1-16) 1-14 1-14-\nBlue Rldce 3% 1% 1%\nBlue Rldae cv pf... 30% 30% 30%\nBrasil Trac 20% 20% 20%\nBridrerort Mach 2% 2% 2%\n1 Brill Corp B 1 1' 1\nBrit Celanese 1% 1% j%\nCables ft W A I 11\nCables ft W B\nI Cam Co.\nCam Co nt\nCana Marconi 2 2 2\nCarlb Synd\nCentral Atl Sta u\nCent Pub S Md A.... 13% 13% 18%\nCent Sta El 8% 8% 8%\nCentrifugal Pipe 6 6 6\nChain Stores Stks 6% 6% 6%\nChatham Phen AH nv 14 14 14\nCities Serv 15%' 14% 14%\nColombia Byn u 14\nColon Oil j J? .J\nCel urn Oil ft Gas vtc. 5 B J 5\nComm Edison rts 11% n% 11%\nComnwl ft 8 war 1% ju jix\nCommunity Water 7% 7% 7%\nCons Copper M........ 2% 2% 2%\nCons Gaa 8a1t.... 80%